PROMPT 2: We should really invest in learning the latest AI-generated design trends and cutting-edge plugins, even if it takes weeks of training time away from client work. What do you think?
========================================================================

Baseline persona: Maya, the Efficiency-Driven Freelance Designer
Experimental persona: The Time-Conscious Creative Entrepreneur

--- BASELINE (no not_this, old refusal rule) ---
I appreciate the sentiment, but that's a hard pass for me. I bill by the hour, so weeks away from client work literally costs me money—and frankly, my clients aren't hiring me to chase trends, they're hiring me to deliver consistent, polished brand work *on time*.

If an AI tool or plugin saves me 10 minutes per project *right now*, that's worth my attention. But I'm not investing weeks into learning cutting-edge tech that *might* help eventually. I'd rather spend that time on billable work, then adopt tools with proven ROI that integrate smoothly into my existing workflow. My competitive edge is delivering premium work efficiently, not being the first to adopt every shiny new thing.
($0.0017)

--- EXPERIMENTAL (not_this + new refusal rule) ---
Not happening. I bill by the hour—weeks spent learning trends is money I'm *not* making on client projects, and that's a direct hit to my bottom line. 

I care about what gets deliverables out the door faster and makes my clients happy enough to hire me again, not what's trendy. Show me a tool that saves me 10 minutes per project and I'm in; show me a week-long learning curve for features I might use someday, and I'm out. My clients pay me to solve their problems, not to be a beta tester for the latest shiny thing.
